1. Overdispersion

1.1 Using Pearson residual

Crabs <- read.table("http://www.stat.ufl.edu/~aa/glm/data/Crabs.dat",header = T)
attach(Crabs)
fit.pois <- glm(y ~ weight, family=poisson) # ML Poisson loglinear
summary(fit.pois)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = y ~ weight, family = poisson)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.9307  -1.9981  -0.5627   0.9298   4.9992  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -0.42841    0.17893  -2.394   0.0167 *  
## weight       0.58930    0.06502   9.064   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for poisson family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 632.79  on 172  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 560.87  on 171  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 920.16
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 5
X2 <- sum(residuals(fit.pois, type="pearson")^2)
phi <- X2/(173 - 2)  # estimate for overdispersion parameter
phi
## [1] 3.133893

1.2 Using residual deviance (with caution)

560.87 / 171  # close but not guaranteed to be consistent
## [1] 3.279942

##

fit.quasi <- glm(y ~ weight, family=quasi(link="log",variance="mu"))

2. Model Diagnostics

2.1 Leverage

hatvalues(fit.quasi) %>% range()
## [1] 0.005959457 0.406547135
plot(1:nrow(Crabs),hatvalues(fit.quasi),pch=19)

2.2 Outlier using residuals

plot(fit.quasi, 3)  # standardized deviance residuals

2.3 Cooks distance

cooks.distance(fit.quasi) %>% range
## [1] 1.015993e-08 6.386057e-01
plot(fit.quasi, 4)  # Cook's distance

plot(fit.quasi, 5)  # std. Pearson residual vs leverage

3. Conditional Logistic regression

model fitting

resp <- levels(logan$occupation)
n <- nrow(logan)
indx <- rep(1:n, length(resp))
logan2 <- data.frame(logan[indx,],
                     id = indx,
                     tocc = factor(rep(resp, each=n)))
logan2$case <- (logan2$occupation == logan2$tocc)
logan2 <- logan2[order(logan2$id),]

## Show dataset for first three strata
logan2[logan2$id %in% c(1,2,3), ]
